Let's analyze this objectively - while the utilization of the term "bitch" is a focal point to Okada's career, Iyo once found herself using the term as well. In terms of delivery, Okada's rendition of the term "bitch" is more muted, and done in a mocking way to make a self aware joke of his English skills by reducing them to few words, with one recurring theme being a swear word, something that is often found with people of younger demographics finding humor in new curse words they are unfamiliar with.

Iyo on the other hand has seemingly only ever used the term "bitch" during her promo battle with Asuka, who was loudly berating her and quickly running away with dictating the momentum of this promo. When Iyo Sky finally got a word in, she used the term "bitch" as a retort, done in a humorous manner, because once again the joke is that Japanese talent likely have a harder time doing promos in English, with the intended effect of making the crowd laugh due to her overly exaggerated antics.

So while the delivery of Iyo's "bitch" vastly outperforms Okada's rendition of the word "bitch", it is he who has made it an intrinsic part of his career and used it to propel himself through riveting and memorable story lines. So in terms off "Who did it better?" it would have to be Okada.

>Can DOOM conquer the cursed summer?
>All Japan Pro Wrestling’s Triple Crown Heavyweight Champion Saito Jun (38) is fired up to overcome his seasonal struggle.

>Jun is staring down a brutal “midsummer tour.”
>First up is his V6 defense against Honda Ryuki at the July 21 show in Edion Arena Osaka's second stadium.
>If he wins, he’ll go on to face the winner of the same show’s number one contender match—Aoyagi Yuma vs Davey Boy Smith Jr.—in a V7 defense in early August.

>Jun is determined to win both matches:
>“First, I’m gonna crush Honda Ryuki. I’ve had it with him stealing my sweets all the time—it’s infuriating.
>And I’m winning again next, no matter who shows up.”
>But one concern remains: his aversion to summer.
>It’s said he doesn’t handle heat well, and this year’s sweltering weather has already cost him 5 kg.

>“How do you know my weight?” Jun laughed, then admitted:
>“Well, no point hiding it—I’m not good with summer.
>My brother’s the same. Back in our sumo days, Rei and I would just wilt together in the July Nagoya tournament…”
>Indeed, he struggled in that event, recording three straight losing records from 2013.
>Perhaps it’s the downside of carrying such an enormous frame.

>And this year, the stress is even worse thanks to Honda’s repeated “snack theft.”
>“Even when I’m trying to sneak in a treat during mountain training, I catch myself looking over my shoulder—like Honda might be there,” Jun said.
>“And then I dreamed he stole my manju. Unforgivable.” He was shaking with rage.

>Still, he’s fighting back:
>reportedly eating around 10 umeboshi a day—local specialties from his hometown of Kakuda—for nourishment and to spark his appetite.
>At the July 17 Korakuen show, Jun clashed fiercely with Honda in an 8-man tag.
>Will the power of plums help him finally overcome summer?
